message.content:
In every derivation issued from the start symbol the first step is

    S  ⇒  NT19 NT43

and NT43 immediately contributes the single terminal  t23 .
Hence everything that precedes the final t23 must be generated by the
non-terminal NT19.

The shape of every string produced by NT19 is extremely restricted,
because NT19 has only the two rules

    NT19 → NT86 NT19
    NT19 → t5

This means: NT19 yields a sequence consisting of

    ( one or more NT86 blocks ) followed by the single token t5.

So, apart from the last t5, the whole prefix of the string has to be a
concatenation of blocks produced by NT86.

Now look at NT86.  It, too, has only two alternatives:

    NT86 → t32                          (a single–token block)
    NT86 → NT23 NT32     (a block that ends with t30)

In particular

• every NT86–block is either just the single token t32, or
• it ends with the token t30 and, in that case, is at least two
  tokens long (because NT23 can never be empty).

Therefore, when the sequence of NT86-blocks is written down,

    – the token t30 can **never** appear immediately after the end of
      a block (because that would make the next block just “t30”,
      which is impossible), and

    – if the substring “t32 t30” occurs, both tokens must belong to
      the **same** NT86-block; for that to happen NT23 would have to be
      able to produce exactly the single token t32.

But NT23 is defined only by

    NT23 → NT88 NT74
    NT23 → NT46 NT62

and none of the right–hand sides can shrink to a single token—each of
them always contributes at least two terminals.  Consequently NT23 can
never produce the single token t32.

Yet the string we are asked to recognise begins with the two adjacent
tokens

    t32 t30 …

so the pattern “t32 t30” is present right at the very start of the part
that has to come from NT19.  As just argued, this pattern cannot appear
in any string that NT19 can generate.

Hence the given string cannot be produced by NT19, and, because NT43
only appends the final t23, the whole string is not in the language of
the grammar.

No
